# Cryptography rules

## Hybrid post-quantum is the default

Every classical primitive ships alongside its lattice counterpart. X25519
ships with ML-KEM-768. Ed25519 ships with ML-DSA-65. The hybrid composition
is non-negotiable — never propose a classical-only operation on the wallet
path. The V4 transition removes the classical half; classical-only today is
V4 deletion debt.

## Per-output PQC keys (Option C)

PQC signing uses per-output KEM-derived keys, not the wallet master key.
Per-output keys give forward secrecy per output. The ML-KEM ciphertext lives
in `tx_extra` under tag `0x06` and must survive pruning permanently — it is
required for wallet PQC key rederivation.

## Test vectors are pinned, not generated

Cryptographic operations have known-answer test vectors in
`docs/test_vectors/*.json`. Vectors are written *before* the implementation.
The implementation is tested against the vectors, not the other way around.
A change to a vector requires explicit review and a CHANGELOG entry — vectors
define consensus and cannot drift silently.

## Wide-reduce, not modular reduction

Scalar derivation from HKDF output uses 64-byte wide reduction
(`Scalar::from_bytes_mod_order_wide`), not 32-byte modular reduction. The
bias difference (2⁻²⁵⁵ vs. 2⁻¹²⁵) is invisible in practice but auditors will
flag the latter. One extra HKDF round is negligible.

## Domain separators on every hash

Every Fiat-Shamir challenge, signature hash, and HKDF derivation includes an
explicit domain separator string and version suffix:

- `"shekyl-output-derive-v1"` for output secret derivation
- `"shekyl-outbound-tx-proof-v3"` for outbound proofs
- `"shekyl-reserve-proof-dleq-v1"` for reserve proof DLEQs

The version suffix is how V4 cleanly invalidates V3 hashes. Forgetting the
version means a future protocol upgrade can't safely change the construction.

## Memwipe is structural, not manual

In Rust, secrets are `Zeroizing<[u8; N]>` or a struct with
`#[derive(Zeroize, ZeroizeOnDrop)]`. Manual memwipe via `let _ = ...` or
explicit drop calls is a code smell — the type system enforces wipe-on-drop,
not the developer's discipline.

In C++, secrets use `crypto::secret_key` or `tools::scrubbed_arr`. Raw
`std::vector<uint8_t>` for secret data is a bug. If you're writing a C++
destructor that calls `memwipe`, ask whether the field should be a wrapped
type instead. See `35-secure-memory.mdc` for full secret-handling rules.

## Direct-write to destination

When Rust returns a secret to C++, the FFI writes directly into the
destination field, not into a scratch buffer that gets copied and wiped. The
scratch pattern requires manual wipe discipline at every call site;
direct-write makes the field's wipe-on-drop semantics handle cleanup
automatically. If you find yourself writing "C++ receives, copies, wipes,"
the FFI signature is wrong — fix the signature.

## Constant-time and trusted randomness

- Side-channel resistance (constant-time operations) is mandatory for all
  crypto code paths.
- All randomness comes from cryptographically secure sources: `OsRng` in
  Rust, `/dev/urandom` or equivalent in C++. Never seed from time, PID, or
  user input.
- Never log, serialize to plaintext, or expose key material in error messages.
